 <p>  Complaints peaked in all boroughs except Staten Island in 2017 and then started going down. Does this explain mean that people got tired of complaining or did city administration kill many rats, reducing its population?</p>
<p> A department of public health and mental hygiene spokesperson said they don’t measure rat population using this data set. But he claimed that places failing rat inspection standards, a measure they use to map areas likely to high number of rats show 60 percent reduction in inspection failures. </p>

